{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639489"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:06:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:06:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17775"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17775"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0,0.38,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10489"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77517"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10489"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17775"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63029"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5402"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24478"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24485"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77517"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her first antenatal visit. She is currently 10 weeks pregnant with her first child. She has a medical history of polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) and is concerned about her risk of developing gestational diabetes. She does not take any regular medications and has no other significant medical history. Her body mass index (BMI) is 28 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a risk factor for gestational diabetes in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Polycystic ovary syndrome","Regular exercise","Body mass index","Young maternal age","First pregnancy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS)\u003C/strong\u003E is a known risk factor for gestational diabetes. Women with PCOS are at an increased risk of insulin resistance, which can contribute to the development of gestational diabetes during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular exercise\u003C/strong\u003E is generally considered a protective factor against gestational diabetes, as it improves insulin sensitivity and maintaining a healthy weight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBody mass index\u003C/strong\u003E (BMI) of 28 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E is considered overweight, which is a risk factor for gestational diabetes. However, in this scenario, the presence of PCOS is a more specific risk factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYoung maternal age\u003C/strong\u003E is not associated with an increased risk of gestational diabetes. Advanced maternal age is more commonly linked to this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E is not a risk factor for gestational diabetes. The risk is more closely associated with factors such as obesity, family history of diabetes, and certain medical conditions like PCOS.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gestational diabetes is more likely to occur in women with a history of polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS).","Other risk factors for gestational diabetes include advanced maternal age, obesity, and a family history of diabetes.","Early identification and management of gestational diabetes is crucial to prevent complications for both the mother and the baby."],"references":["Preda A, Stefan AG, Vladu IM, Fortofoiu MC, Clenciu D, Fortofoiu M, Gheorghe IO, Comanescu AC, Mota M. Analysis of Risk Factors for the Development of Gestational Diabetes Mellitus in a Group of Romanian Patients. J Diabetes Res. 2022 Jun 2;2022:2367213. doi: 10.1155/2022/2367213. PMID: 35694616; PMCID: PMC9184202.","Amiri FN, Faramarzi M, Bakhtiari A, Omidvar S. Risk Factors for Gestational Diabetes Mellitus: A Case-Control Study. Am J Lifestyle Med. 2018 Aug 9;15(2):184-190. doi: 10.1177/1559827618791980. PMID: 33786034; PMCID: PMC7958210.","Farahvar S, Walfisch A, Sheiner E. Gestational diabetes risk factors and long-term consequences for both mother and offspring: a literature review. Expert Rev Endocrinol Metab. 2019 Jan;14(1):63-74. doi: 10.1080/17446651.2018.1476135. Epub 2018 Jun 5. PMID: 30063409."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63029"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17775"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63029"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T10:58:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T10:59:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10489"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77517"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt